unset over the Rio Negro, a couple of kilometers upstream from Manaus Country/Countries in which the site lies Countries /wiki/Colombia Colombia Colombia, /wiki/Venezuela Venezuela Venezuela, /wiki/Brazil Brazil Brazil Source name Source unnamed Source location  - location /wiki/Department_of_Guain%C3%ADa Department of Guainía Department of Guainía, /wiki/Amazon_Region_of_Colombia Amazon Region of Colombia Amazon Region of Colombia, /wiki/Colombia Colombia Colombia Mouth name Mouth /wiki/Amazon_River Amazon River Amazon River Mouth location  - location /wiki/Manaus Manaus Manaus, /wiki/Amazonas_(Brazilian_state) Amazonas (Brazilian state) Amazonas State, /wiki/Brazil Brazil Brazil Mouth geographic coordinates  - coordinates http://toolserver.org/~geohack/geohack.php?pagename=Rio_Negro_(Amazon)&params=3_08_00_S_59_54_30_W_type:river_region:CO Maps, aerial photos, and other data for this location 3°08?00?S 59°54?30?W? / ? Maps, aerial photos, and other data for this location 3.1333333°S 59.90833°W? / -3.1333333; -59.90833 Length Length 2,230 km (1,390 mi) approx. Drainage basin/catchment area/watershed Basin 691,000 km2 (267,000 sq mi) Discharge figures measured at Discharge /wiki/Mouth_(river) Mouth (river) mouth Average discharge  - average 28,000 m3/s (988,800 cu ft/s) #cite_note-0 [1] /wiki/File:Negroamazonrivermap.png Map showing the Rio Negro in the Amazon River basin. Map showing the Rio Negro in the Amazon River basin. Rio Negro ( /wiki/Portuguese_language Portuguese language Portuguese: Rio Negro, /wiki/Spanish_language Spanish language Spanish: Río Negro, /wiki/English_language English language English: Black River) is the largest left tributary of the /wiki/Amazon_River Amazon River Amazon and the largest /wiki/Blackwater_river Blackwater river blackwater river in the world. It has its sources along the watershed between the /wiki/Orinoco Orinoco Orinoco and the Amazon basins, and also connects with the Orinoco by way of the /wiki/Casiquiare_canal Casiquiare canal Casiquiare canal in southern /wiki/Venezuela Venezuela Venezuela. In Colombia, where the Rio Negro's sources are located, it is called the Guainía River. Its main affluent is the /wiki/Vaup%C3%A9s_River Vaupés River Vaupés, which disputes with the headwaters of the /wiki/Guaviare_River Guaviare River Guaviare branch of the /wiki/Orinoco Orinoco Orinoco, the drainage of the eastern slope of the /wiki/Andes Andes Andes of /wiki/Colombia Colombia Colombia. The Rio Negro flows into the Rio Solimões to form the Amazon River South of /wiki/Manaus Manaus Manaus, /wiki/Brazil Brazil Brazil. Rio Negro is navigable for 700 kilometres (430 mi) from its mouth in 1 metre of water in the dry season, but it has many sandbanks and minor difficulties. A small portion of it forms the international boundary between Colombia and Venezuela. In the /wiki/Wet_season Wet season wet season, it floods the country far and wide, sometimes to a width of 30 kilometres (19 mi), for long distances, and for 650 kilometres (400 mi) upstream. During this time, from April until October, it is a succession of lagoons, full of long islands and intricate channels as far as /wiki/Santa_Isabel_do_Rio_Negro Santa Isabel do Rio Negro Santa Isabel do Rio Negro. The foothills of the Andes begin just before reaching the /wiki/Vaup%C3%A9s_River Vaupés River Vaupés River. At this point, the Negro narrows and is filled with many large rocks over which it violently flows in cataracts, rapids and whirlpools. Despite the impediments, canoes and motor launches ascend past /wiki/S%C3%A3o_Gabriel_da_Cachoeira São Gabriel da Cachoeira São Gabriel da Cachoeira to the /wiki/Andes Andes Andes. /wiki/File:Manaus_Encontro_das_aguas_10_2006_103_8x6.jpg /wiki/File:Manaus_Encontro_das_aguas_10_2006_103_8x6.jpg Enlarge The mouth of the Rio Negro at the " /wiki/Meeting_of_Waters Meeting of Waters Meeting of Waters": the dark Rio Negro meeting the silty Amazon River. While the name Rio Negro means Black River, its waters aren't exactly black; they are similar in color to strong /wiki/Tea Tea tea. The dark color comes from /wiki/Humic_acid Humic acid humic acid from incomplete breakdown of phenol-containing vegetation from sandy clearings. The river's name arises from the fact that it looks black from afar. Much has been written on the productivity of the Rio Negro and other blackwater rivers. The older idea that these are "hunger rivers" is giving way, with new research, to the recognition that the Rio Negro, for example, supports a large fishing industry and has numerous turtle beaches. If the Negro was empty of Indians during the 17th century, introduced exotic diseases and warfare are more likely causes than low river productivity. [ /w/index.php?title=Rio_Negro_(Amazon)&action=edit&section=1 Edit section: Notes edit] Notes #cite_ref-0 ^ Seyler, Patrick; Laurence Maurice-Bourgoin, Jean Loup Guyot. http://www.cprm.gov.br/pgagem/Manuscripts/seylerp.htm "Hydrological Control on the Temporal Variability of Trace Element Concentration in the Amazon River and its Main Tributaries". Geological Survey of Brazil (CPRM). http://www.cprm.gov.br/pgagem/Manuscripts/seylerp.htm http://www.cprm.gov.br/pgagem/Manuscripts/seylerp.htm. Retrieved 24 July 2010. ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&rft.genre=bookitem&rft.btitle=Hydrological+Control+on+the+Temporal+Variability+of+Trace+Element+Concentration+in+the+Amazon+River+and+its+Main+Tributaries&rft.atitle=&rft.aulast=Seyler&rft.aufirst=Patrick&rft.au=Seyler%2C%26%2332%3BPatrick&rft.pub=Geological+Survey+of+Brazil+%28CPRM%29&rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.cprm.gov.br%2Fpgagem%2FManuscripts%2Fseylerp.htm&rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Rio_Negro_(Amazon)   [ /w/index.php?title=Rio_Negro_(Amazon)&action=edit&section=2 Edit section: References edit] References Goulding, M., Carvalho, M. L., & Ferreira, E. J. G. (1988). Rio Negro, rich life in poor water : Amazonian diversity and foodchain ecology as seen through fish communit